014-04-16 05:34:22','2014-04-16 05:34:22','',10,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/2014/04/16/10-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(15,1,'2014-04-16 05:40:32','2014-04-16 05:40:32',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','15','','','2014-05-14 15:42:14','2014-05-14 15:42:14','',8,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/?p=15',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(16,1,'2014-04-16 05:40:32','2014-04-16 05:40:32',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','16','','','2014-05-14 15:42:14','2014-05-14 15:42:14','',0,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/?p=16',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(17,1,'2014-04-16 05:42:02','2014-04-16 05:42:02','<h3>Mission</h3>\r\nRecent advances in genome sequencing and in web technologies have taken us to the the edge of a new world, where studying the genomes of microbial samples could lead to enormous benefits for public health, clinical treatments and the study of infectious diseases. However in order to make this a reality we need tools to enable clinicians, public health workers and biologists to make decisions and discoveries. Our goals with the myKrobe suite of tools are\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>To build tools which provide precisely the information needed to enable diagnostic or treatment decisions in the clinic.</li>\r\n	<li>To build extremely user-friendly tools which enable people to study specific microbial samples, either in and of themselves, or in the context of global diversity.</li>\r\n	<li>To enable seamless world-wide sharing of microbial genomes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3>Team</h3>\r\nmyKrobe is developed at the Wellcome Trust Centre for Human Genetics (University of Oxford) in Zamin Iqbal’s <a title=\"lab\" href=\"http://www.well.ox.ac.uk/iqbal\">lab</a>, by himself and Phelim Bradley, in collaboration with Claire Gordon, Tanya Golubchik, Louise Pankhurst, and Luke Anson in the labs of Tim Peto and Derrick Crooke (John Radcliffe Hospital, Oxford).\r\n\r\nWe are grateful for funding from the Nuffield Division of Medicine (Oxford), the Wellcome Trust, the Royal Society and the Li Ka Shing Foundation.','About','','publish','closed','closed','','about','','','2014-05-14 15:48:59','2014-05-14 15:48:59','',0,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/?page_id=17',2,'page','',0),(18,1,'2014-04-16 05:42:02','2014-04-16 05:42:02','<h3>Mission</h3>\r\nWe have two overriding goals for myKrobe:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>To provide tools that can be used by clinicians, epidemiologists and hospitals which enable them to make decisions, study diseases, and track resistance profiles, but do not need continual “tweaking” by bioinformatic experts.</li>\r\n	<li>To enable seamless world-wide sharing of microbial genomes in a way that allows people to compare their samples with everything that has gone before. If we can allow everyone to share and study all the data, we can make progress together.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nMyKrobe was developed at the Wellcome Trust Centre for Human Genetics (University of Oxford) in Zamin Iqbal’s lab, by himself and Phelim Bradley, in collaboration with Claire Gordon, Tanya Golubchik, David Wyllie, Tim Peto and Derrick Crooke at the John Radcliffe Hospital, Oxford.','About','','inherit','closed','closed','','17-revision-v1','','','2014-04-16 05:42:02','2014-04-16 05:42:02','',17,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/2014/04/16/17-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(19,1,'2014-04-16 05:42:32','2014-04-16 05:42:32',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','19','','','2014-05-14 15:42:14','2014-05-14 15:42:14','',0,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/?p=19',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(20,1,'2014-04-16 05:42:32','2014-04-16 05:42:32','','Contact','','publish','closed','closed','','contact','','','2014-05-14 15:42:14','2014-05-14 15:42:14','',0,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/?p=20',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(21,1,'2014-04-17 05:28:58','2014-04-17 05:28:58','','Predictor','','inherit','closed','closed','','10-revision-v1','','','2014-04-17 05:28:58','2014-04-17 05:28:58','',10,'http://clients.simonheys.com/mykrobe/2014/04/17/